Barack Obama will be the fourth American president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize
US President Barack Obama will fly to Oslo in Norway, to spend 26 hours there and be the fourth American history president to receive the Nobel Peace Prize.
He will be awarded the diploma, medal and cheque of $1.4 million, among other things, for his exceptional efforts to strengthen global diplomacy and collaboration among nations.
The White House Chief and his wife Michelle will land in the morning in the Norwegian metropolis and have a busy schedule.
He will first go to the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time the five members of the Committee who chose him in October among 172 people and 33 organizations.
The planning of the presidential couple then provides for an interview with the king of Norway Harald V and Queen Sonja.
The visit will meet its summit in the afternoon at a solemn ceremony where Obama will receive the prestigious reward.
He will be the fourth American President to receive it, but only the third to be awarded the prize within the Committee itself.
The White House informed in advance that Obama would talk about the war in Afghanistan when the prize was released.
The President does not want to avoid this because he is aware that he receives this prize by being a president who is waging a war in two countries at present.
He strengthened the war effort a few days ago by sending additional units to Afghanistan, which none of his critics would forget to mention.
At the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a degree and a cheque of ten million Swedish crowns (about 1.1 million Euros).
He intends to donate to charitable works, but he has not yet decided on which.
His program will then take him and his wife to a banquet including, in addition to the king and queen of Norway, the head of government and 250 other guests.
Obama was rather reluctant at this price at the beginning.
He mentioned, for example, feeling that he did not fully deserve it.
He also repeated several times that it is not a price for himself, but for all those who uphold the same values as him.
From the time of the announcement, he stated that it would be an "invitation to act."
