This leads to the most problems throughout Obama's strategy seems to be his intention to withdraw the armies of Afghanistan in 18 months and to end this whole process in three years' time. Obama's entire doctrine brings more questions than it provides.
Many doubt the fact that a half-increase will bring the same results as the progress in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, the Iraqi society is relatively well organized and its leaders honour the agreements.
The situation in Afghanistan is marked by the opposite - no one can count on, and no treaty is respected.
Under these conditions, it is difficult to prepare Afghan security forces, accustomed to changing their leadership from day to day according to what arranges them.
Political institutions, although officially founded, will remain purely powder in the eyes behind which will proliferate patriarchal ethnic relations.
It is particularly complex to balance the interests of various ethnic groups in the light of the lack of clarity in relation to relations, which are still complicated by Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the foundation of a "ready-to-act state", which is the basic goal of the operation, does not seem to be very real.
The temporal horizon of Obama's strategy makes it perplexed by its voluntarism.
In the past eight years, the situation in Afghanistan has only gotten worse and is currently on the brink of chaos.
Only a purely romantic heart and out of reality can be persuaded that the small soldiers sent into the tumult of the war for their "promple return to the house" will bring there a true miracle.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is purely irresponsible, since the Taliban will regard it as the indirect confession of the US defeat.
