Discrimination at work has increased in recent years, especially for women of young generations who want to be mothers.
This is what the study "Fecundity and career of women in Spain" carried out by the CSIC in collaboration with the Institute of Women.
The survey, conducted out of 9,737 women aged 15 to 75, leaves no doubt: 75 per cent of working mothers had a limited career because of maternity.
The study indicates that there are many differences between the start of life in couples and the number of children, whether or not women work and the type of employment.
Those who have no activity outside the home, work part-time or have a unstable job, get married earlier, have their first pregnancy earlier and have more children.
On the other hand, women with stable employment, mainly in the public sector, are reversing entry into marriage and the first pregnancy, and have fewer children.
Women between 35 and 49 years of fixed employment have their first child, on average, 3.7 years after having settled in a couple. This figure goes to 4.1 for those working in the public sector. "This data shows that women with stable employment needed more time in their lives to get it, which led them to push back the union and the arrival of children.
In addition, the type of employment exerted has a significant influence on maternity, but less on the date of common begin-of-life," says CSIC researcher Margarita Delgado.
The level of studies is another factor that widens the age gap of women's marriage and their first child.
According to the survey, the higher the level of training, the more they get married and have their first child late.
The difference is also maintained among women of the same generation.
For example, in the 35-49 age group, those who did elementary and higher studies were mothers for the first time at 25.1 and at 32.1 years on average, respectively.
"Another distinction also appears among women, depending on their level of study.
