Emergency braking aid is now mandatory
As this has taken place with the ABS braking system and as this will take place with ESP stability control, emergency braking aid systems will be a mandatory component on European cars.
They are already mandatory on newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while for the rest of the vehicles a period of shortage has been fixed until the end of February 2011.
The aim of the measure, imposed by the European Union, is to strengthen the protection of pedestrians, even if, by its mode of action, it can also help to avoid many back shocks.
The emergency braking assistant acts by increasing pressure on the brakes in case of emergency detected by the system thanks to the driver's kick.
But the latter does not always keep the pressure to the end.
According to a study conducted by the Bosch car manufacturer, one third of drivers involved in an accident could not support the brake before the collision, and half of them had not benefited from all of its strength.
Up to 1 100 accidents
The intervention of the aid, on the other hand, requires the maximum of the brake system, reducing the distance the car needs to stop.
According to an EU study, if all cars were equipped with such elements, up to 1,100 fatal accidents in which pedestrians are involved could be avoided each year.
This reduction would be even more important with the popularization of the so-called emergency braking systems: it is estimated that one in four disasters with injuries would be avoided.
In this case, the vehicle is equipped with a system that, thanks to radar or camera, detects obstacles and prevents the driver, in addition to acting slightly on the brakes.
If the driver reacts, it helps by increasing pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
